AutoPrimer3

AutoPrimer3<span class="T11">retrieves gene information, DNA sequences</span><span class="T11">and SNP information</span>from the UCSC genome browser<span class="T11">and uses primer3 (</span>[<span class="T11">http://primer3.sourceforge.net/</span>](http://primer3.sourceforge.net/)<span class="T11">) to automatically</span>design primers to genes or genomic coordinate targets. An internet connection is required by the program to retrieve database information from the UCSC genome browser.

Designing

<div class="P2"><div style="height:1.9791in;width:4.1547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:6.7559cm; " class="fr1" id="Image1">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

At startup the 'Genes' tab is shown.

Select the desired genome for the species you want to design primers for using the<span class="T1"> 'Genome'</span> menu.

Hover the mouse cursor over the loaded genome for its full description

<div class="P2"><div style="height:1.9791in;width:4.1547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0.127cm; " class="fr2" id="Image2">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

Once the genome information is loaded you may select the desired<span class="T1">gene database</span>.

<div class="P2"><div style="height:2.7335in;width:4.1547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:6.747cm; " class="fr1" id="Image3">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

And, if available, you may select a<span class="T1">SNP database</span> in order to prevent primers from being designed on top of any coordinates that match SNPs in the given database.

The<span class="T1">'Design to...'</span>menu allows you to choose between designing only to coding regions or to all exons of gene targets.

The<span class="T1">'Min distance'</span> field lets you choose the minimum distance in base pairs<span class="T5">(bp)</span>between targets and primers.

The<span class="T1">'Flanking region'</span> field<span class="T5">tells AutoPrimer3 how many bp of flanking DNA to retrieve either side of target regions to use for its primer designs.</span>

<div class="P4"><div style="height:1.9902in;width:4.1547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:-0.0249cm; " class="fr3" id="Image4">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

Enter one or more gene symbols or transcript Ids in the<span class="T1">'Gene(s)'</span> input box and either press Enter or click the<span class="T1">'Design'</span> button to start designing primers. If a gene symbol is used primers will be designed to all transcripts found for the given gene in the relevant database.

<div class="P9"><div style="height:2in;width:4.1547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0.1021cm; " class="fr3" id="Image5">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div><div style="position:relative; left:0.1021cm;">Alternatively,<span class="T6">you may enter coordinates to design primers to as shown below using the input box on the</span><span class="T2">'Coordinates'</span><span class="T6">tab.</span></div></div>

Alternatively, you may use the<span class="T1">'Load File'</span> button to load up to 100 regions from a BED or VCF file or a text file with regions specified as intervals (i.e. in the format chr1:1000-2000).

<div class="P10"><div style="height:2in;width:4.1547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:6.7729cm; " class="fr3" id="Image6">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

The<span class="T1">'Primer3 Settings'</span> tab provides various options to be passed to<span class="T7">the</span> primer3<span class="T7">(</span>[<span class="T7">http://primer3.sourceforge.net/</span>](http://primer3.sourceforge.net/)<span class="T7">) program</span> when designing primers.<span class="T7">Three mispriming libraries are available: human, rodent and drosophila.</span>

Results

Once designs are completed a new window will appear with the results. You may use the associated<span class="T1">'File'</span> menu to save the output of each tab. Note that if choosing .xlsx output for saving primers the output consists of two worksheets, one giving the primers in a list (one row per primer, which may be useful for copying and pasting into certain primer purchasing websites) and one giving more detailed output like that shown by the AutoPrimer3 Results window.

The first tab of the results window contains a table of the primer targets and designs. Most of the fields are self-explanatory but the final column provides a hyperlink to perform in-silico PCR at the UCSC genome browser in order to check for the specificity of the primer pairs.

<div class="P12"><div style="height:4.8681in;width:6.9252in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0cm; " class="fr4" id="Image7">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

Note that gene exons are counted from the first exon of all relevant transcripts, even if that exon is non-coding and the user has chosen only to design to coding regions. So, the first exon target may not necessarily be numbered '1'.

The<span class="T3">'D</span><span class="T1">esign</span><span class="T3">D</span><span class="T1">etails</span><span class="T3">'</span> tab provides<span class="T8">output from</span> primer3 for each design attempted.

<div class="P12"><div style="height:3.4035in;width:5.7547in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0.7201cm; " class="fr4" id="Image8">![](data:image/*;base64,)</div></div>

<span class="T9">When designing primers to genes, t</span>he<span class="T1">'Gene Reference Sequences'</span> tab<span class="T9">provides the DNA sequence for your target exons plus flanking sequence either side (the length of which is determined by the value used in the</span><span class="T4">'Flanking region'</span><span class="T9"> field when the primers were designed). If there were multiple target regions (either multiple genes/transcripts specified or genes that map to multiple genomic regions) the choice box towards the bottom right of the window can be used to switch between the relevant reference sequences.</span>
